+---
+date: "2026-06-11"
+status: done
+implements: [FR-E83]
+tags: [engine, cli, housekeeping, journal]
+related_tasks:
+  - 2026/05/durable-run-lifecycle-replay.md
+  - 2026/05/per-workflow-run-lock.md
+---
+# engine: `runs prune` — safe cleanup of old runs
+
+## Goal
+
+Add a `runs prune` CLI subcommand that deletes the oldest run directories
+under `<workflow-dir>/runs/` while never touching non-terminal, locked, or
+unreplayable runs, so operators can reclaim disk space without risking a
+live or recoverable run.
+
+## Overview
+
+### Context
+
+Run directories accumulate under `<workflowDir>/runs/<run-id>/` (worktree,
+node artifacts, logs, journal) and are never cleaned up. The only durable
+record of a run is its append-only `journal.jsonl` (FR-E69); run status and
+start time are obtained exclusively by replaying it with the existing
+replayer in `src/state/run-journal.ts`. The per-workflow lock file
+`runs/.lock` (FR-E54) names the run currently held by a live engine
+process.
+
+### Current State
+
+- `src/state/state.ts` — `getRunDir(runId, workflowDir)` is the single
+  source of run-directory paths.
+- `src/state/run-journal.ts` — `replayRunJournal(runDir)` reconstructs
+  `RunState` (incl. `status`, `started_at`) from `journal.jsonl`; throws on
+  missing file, malformed non-tail records, or missing `run_started`.
+- `src/state/lock.ts` — `defaultLockPath(workflowDir)` +
+  `readLockInfo(lockPath)` expose the `.lock` location and content
+  (`{ pid, hostname, run_id, started_at }`).
+- `src/cli.ts` — hand-rolled arg parsing per subcommand (`parseArgs`,
+  `parseAnswerArgs`), `resolveActiveWorkflow` (FR-E78) fallback when the
+  workflow is omitted, `printUsage()` for `--help`.
+- No `runs` subcommand exists.
+
+### Constraints
+
+- Reuse existing helpers (`getRunDir`, `replayRunJournal`,
+  `defaultLockPath`/`readLockInfo`); no duplicated path construction or
+  replay logic; no new dependencies.
+- Safety rules (hard): never delete non-terminal runs (replayed status not
+  in `completed|failed|aborted`); never delete the run referenced by an
+  existing `runs/.lock`; missing/unreplayable journal counts as
+  NOT terminal (keep + report skip reason).
+- `--keep` must be a non-negative integer; anything else → clear error,
+  non-zero exit. `--dry-run` prints what would be deleted, deletes
+  nothing, exits 0.
+- Follow `src/cli.ts` argument-parsing style; subcommand appears in
+  `--help` output.
+- `deno task check` stays green; FR registered in
+  `documents/requirements-engine/06-distribution-and-housekeeping.md`.
+- **Keep-budget semantics (decision):** the `--keep N` budget counts only
+  deletable runs (terminal + unlocked + replayable). Skipped runs remain
+  in addition to the N kept — safety rules dominate the "at most N remain"
+  goal; a flood of non-terminal runs must never force deletion of recent
+  terminal history.
+
+## Definition of Done
+
+- [x] FR-E83: Prune selection keeps the N newest deletable runs (by
+      replayed `started_at`) and deletes the older ones.
+      Test: `src/state/prune_test.ts::FR-E83 prune — keeps N newest terminal runs, deletes older ones`.
+      Evidence: `deno task test src/state/prune_test.ts`.
+- [x] FR-E83: Non-terminal runs are never deleted, regardless of `--keep`.
+      Test: `src/state/prune_test.ts::FR-E83 prune — skips non-terminal runs even with keep 0`.
+      Evidence: `deno task test src/state/prune_test.ts`.
+- [x] FR-E83: The run referenced by an existing `runs/.lock` is never
+      deleted.
+      Test: `src/state/prune_test.ts::FR-E83 prune — skips the run referenced by runs/.lock`.
+      Evidence: `deno task test src/state/prune_test.ts`.
+- [x] FR-E83: Missing or unreplayable `journal.jsonl` counts as
+      non-terminal — kept and reported skipped with the reason.
+      Test: `src/state/prune_test.ts::FR-E83 prune — missing or unreplayable journal counts as non-terminal`.
+      Evidence: `deno task test src/state/prune_test.ts`.
+- [x] FR-E83: `--keep 0` deletes all terminal unlocked runs.
+      Test: `src/state/prune_test.ts::FR-E83 prune — keep 0 deletes all terminal unlocked runs`.
+      Evidence: `deno task test src/state/prune_test.ts`.
+- [x] FR-E83: `--dry-run` deletes nothing while reporting the would-be
+      deletions.
+      Test: `src/state/prune_test.ts::FR-E83 prune — dry-run deletes nothing`.
+      Evidence: `deno task test src/state/prune_test.ts`.
+- [x] FR-E83: Bad `--keep` values (missing, negative, non-integer,
+      non-numeric) are rejected with a clear error.
+      Test: `src/cli_test.ts::FR-E83 parseRunsPruneArgs — rejects bad --keep values`.
+      Evidence: `deno task test src/cli_test.ts`.
+- [x] FR-E83: `runs prune` appears in CLI `--help` output.
+      Test: `src/cli_test.ts::FR-E83 CLI --help lists the runs prune subcommand`.
+      Evidence: `deno task test src/cli_test.ts`.
+- [x] FR-E83: SRS section added to
+      `documents/requirements-engine/06-distribution-and-housekeeping.md`
+      with acceptance references; SRS index + `documents/index.md` rows
+      added. Evidence: `deno task check`.
+- [x] FR-E83: Full verification passes. Test: `deno task check`.
+      Evidence: `deno task check`.
+
+## Solution
+
+### Selected Variant
+
+Architecturally-correct (V2 of 3): a dedicated `src/state/prune.ts` module
+owning the selection + deletion logic, with `cli.ts` contributing only the
+`runs prune` arg parser and dispatch. Rejected V1 (all-inline in `cli.ts`:
+untestable without subprocess spawns, bloats the entry point) and V3
+(general `runs` command-group infrastructure with listing: listing is
+explicitly out of scope, infra has no second consumer yet). Selection made
+autonomously (benchmark non-interactive mode); V2 is the only variant that
+satisfies the reuse constraint, the unit-test constraint, and the scope
+boundary simultaneously.
+
+### Files to Create or Modify
+
+- **New `src/state/prune.ts`** — prune planning + execution:
+  - `interface RunPruneDecision { run_id: string; action: "delete" | "keep" | "skip"; reason?: string; started_at?: string }`
+  - `interface RunsPruneReport { workflow_dir: string; dry_run: boolean; deleted: RunPruneDecision[]; kept: RunPruneDecision[]; skipped: RunPruneDecision[] }`
+  - `planRunsPrune(workflowDir, keep)` — enumerate directories under
+    `<workflowDir>/runs/` (stray non-directory entries such as `.lock` are
+    ignored silently, not reported as skipped runs; absent dir → empty
+    plan);
+    read the lock once via `readLockInfo(defaultLockPath(workflowDir))`
+    (any read/parse error → no locked run); per run dir replay the journal
+    via `replayRunJournal(getRunDir(runId, workflowDir))`:
+    - replay throws → `skip`, reason `journal missing or unreplayable: <msg>`;
+    - lock names the run → `skip`, reason `referenced by runs/.lock`;
+    - status not in `completed|failed|aborted` → `skip`, reason
+      `non-terminal status: <status>`;
+    - else deletable candidate with `started_at` from the replayed state.
+    Sort candidates newest-first by `started_at` (run-id tiebreak for
+    determinism); first `keep` → `keep`, rest → `delete`. Throws on
+    negative/non-integer `keep` (defence in depth behind CLI validation).
+  - `pruneRuns({ workflowDir, keep, dryRun })` — run the plan; when not
+    dry-run, `Deno.remove(getRunDir(...), { recursive: true })` each
+    `delete` entry; return the report.
+- **`src/cli.ts`**:
+  - `interface RunsPruneArgs { workflowDir?: string; keep: number; dryRun: boolean }`
+  - `parseRunsPruneArgs(args)` (exported, mirrors `parseAnswerArgs` style):
+    accepts `--workflow <p>` / `--workflow=<p>` (normalised),
+    `--keep <N>` / `--keep=<N>`, `--dry-run`; rejects missing `--keep`,
+    non-integer/negative values, and unexpected positionals with clear
+    errors.
+  - `runRunsPrune(args)` — parse; fall back to `resolveActiveWorkflow`
+    when `--workflow` omitted (FR-E78 rule, same as `answer`); call
+    `pruneRuns`; print the summary (deleted/kept/skipped counts, per-run
+    skip reasons, `[dry-run] would delete` prefix in dry-run); exit 0 on
+    success, exit 1 on error (matches `runAnswer`).
+  - Dispatch `runs prune` in `import.meta.main`; unknown `runs` sub →
+    usage + exit 1. Add the command to `printUsage()`.
+- **New `src/state/prune_test.ts`** — temp-dir fixtures with engine-shaped
+  journals written via `RunJournalWriter` (same helper style as
+  `lifecycle-replay_test.ts`): terminal run = `run_started` +
+  `run_completed`/`run_failed`; non-terminal = `run_started` only;
+  unreplayable = garbage `journal.jsonl`; missing = bare directory; locked
+  = `runs/.lock` JSON naming a run. Covers the seven DoD behaviours.
+- **`src/cli_test.ts`** — `parseRunsPruneArgs` cases (happy path, `=`
+  forms, bad `--keep`, unexpected positional) + `--help` spawn asserting
+  `runs prune` is listed.
+- **Docs** — SRS section `### 3.83 FR-E83` in
+  `06-distribution-and-housekeeping.md`; FR map row in
+  `requirements-engine.md`; row in `documents/index.md`; SDS note in
+  `documents/design-engine/01-engine-modules-core.md` (state module list);
+  `printUsage()` already covers user-facing help (README untouched —
+  housekeeping subcommand, not an install/usage-flow change).
+
+### Error Handling Strategy
+
+Fail fast and keep when in doubt: every per-run replay failure is caught
+and converted into a `skip` decision carrying the underlying message —
+never into a delete. Lock read errors mean "no run is provably locked"
+(absent/corrupt lock cannot reference a run); a corrupt lock therefore
+never blocks pruning of other runs but also never marks anything
+deletable that replay didn't prove terminal. CLI-level validation errors
+(`--keep`) print `Error: <msg>` and exit 1 before any filesystem mutation.
+Deletion errors propagate (no swallowing) — a partial prune reports loudly
+via the thrown error.
+
+### Verification Commands
+
+- `deno task test src/state/prune_test.ts`
+- `deno task test src/cli_test.ts`
+- `deno task check`
+
+## Follow-ups
+
+- `runs list` / inspection output (explicitly out of scope here).
+- Age-based pruning (`--older-than`) if operators ask for it.
+- Deleted run dirs may contain per-run git worktrees (FR-E57); plain
+  recursive removal leaves stale-but-harmless metadata under the main
+  repo's `.git/worktrees` that `git worktree prune` self-heals. Engine
+  stays git-free by decision, so no `git worktree remove` call here.
